    "rawPassageText": "READING PASSAGE 1\n\nHow running shoes have changed\n\nYou should spend about 20 minutes on Questions 1–13, which are based on Reading Passage 1 below.\n\nIn 2019, the fictional British long-distance runner Clara Benson won her first major international marathon after several seasons of promising but uneven performances. Her victory surprised many commentators. Four years earlier, Benson had been regarded as a talented athlete who could compete with elite runners but rarely threatened to beat them in the biggest races.\n\nSeveral changes helped explain Benson’s improvement. One was obvious: in 2017, she began working with a former Olympic coach who changed her training schedule and racing strategy. Another change was far less noticeable. For years, Benson had used a traditional racing shoe with a thin sole and limited cushioning. In 2018, however, she began competing in a shoe with a thicker layer of lightweight foam and a curved plate embedded in the midsole. This alteration was small in appearance, but its effect on her running economy was significant.\n\nThe change Benson made is one example of the many options available to runners who wish to adjust their footwear. “Elite athletes rarely race in shoes taken directly from a shop shelf,” says Martin Vale, a specialist shoe technician based in Manchester. “Their shoes are usually adapted to their foot shape, running style and event distance. At the highest level, even a tiny difference can matter.” As a result, the shoes worn by leading runners are often not identical to the commercial versions available to ordinary customers.\n\nThe American middle-distance runners Daniel and Marcus Rahman, for example, have long been known for their exact footwear requirements. “We are extremely specific about our racing shoes,” they explain. “The shoes are first produced by our sponsor, but then they are sent to a workshop where the fit, sole stiffness and upper material are checked again.” They have experimented not only with different sole shapes, but also with different kinds of dye used on the shoe uppers. Their current racing shoes are slightly heavier than the average elite model and have a firmer plate beneath the forefoot.\n\nThe main reason for such modifications is simple: the difference between winning and losing in elite running can be measured in seconds, or even fractions of a second. Runners and their support teams are therefore increasingly willing to test unusual adjustments if these may provide a competitive advantage.\n\nFootwear modification has a longer history than many people realise. In the 1960s, some track athletes began altering the arrangement of metal pins in their spikes to improve grip on different surfaces. In the 1980s, a small number of experimental shoes appeared with spring-like structures under the heel. One such model produced so much recoil that officials banned it from competition, arguing that it gave runners an artificial advantage. Since then, rule makers have paid close attention to developments in shoe technology.\n\nToday, shoe adjustment is considered by many coaches to be as important as nutrition or training. Modifications can be divided into two main categories: changes to the upper part of the shoe and changes to the sole. The sole is usually the more important area, as it affects cushioning, stability and energy return. Athletes may change their shoes depending on the race distance, the running surface and the weather. High temperatures, for instance, can make certain foams softer, while wet conditions may require a different outsole pattern.\n\nIn the early days of modern running, most shoes were made from leather. This material was strong, but it absorbed water and became heavy in rain. Synthetic materials later became common because they were lighter, cheaper and easier to shape. Nylon mesh allowed better ventilation, while thermoplastic overlays helped support the foot without adding much weight. More recently, advanced foams have become central to racing-shoe design. These foams are designed to compress when the runner lands and then expand quickly as the foot leaves the ground.\n\nOf all recent developments, carbon plates have attracted the most discussion. These plates are often placed inside the midsole and are designed to guide the foot forward during toe-off. Tests suggest that, when combined with suitable foam, a curved plate can reduce the amount of energy a runner uses at a given speed. In this sense, modern racing shoes have changed not only the equipment athletes wear but also the style of racing itself.\n\nSome runners go beyond standard adjustments. The Spanish sprinter Mateo Ruiz once had three additional steel pins placed near the front of each shoe because he believed they improved his drive from the starting blocks. His coaches later claimed that this change contributed to his unusually powerful acceleration. Other athletes focus on comfort rather than speed. The Portuguese marathon runner Sofia Almeida replaced the original laces in her shoes with thinner elastic ones because the standard version created pressure across the top of her foot.\n\nRunning-shoe customisation has raised performance standards in ways that would have been difficult to imagine when athletes competed in heavy leather shoes with simple rubber soles. As materials continue to develop, further changes are almost certain, although sports authorities will continue to debate where useful innovation ends and unfair assistance begins.\n\nQuestions 1–7\n\nDo the following statements agree with the information given in Reading Passage 1?\n\nIn boxes 1–7 on your answer sheet, write\n\nTRUE if the statement agrees with the information\nFALSE if the statement contradicts the information\nNOT GIVEN if there is no information on this\n\n1 People had expected Clara Benson to become a major marathon winner for several years before 2019.\n2 The change Clara Benson made to her shoes was widely noticed by the public.\n3 Most elite runners travel with a specialist shoe technician during competitions.\n4 Daniel and Marcus Rahman use racing shoes that are lighter than most elite models.\n5 The spring-like shoe banned in the 1980s was designed by a former Olympic runner.\n6 Weather conditions can influence the type of shoe adjustment a runner makes.\n7 Mateo Ruiz’s coaches believed that a change to his shoes helped his acceleration.\n\nQuestions 8–13\n\nComplete the notes below.\n\nChoose ONE WORD ONLY from the passage for each answer.\n\nWrite your answers in boxes 8–13 on your answer sheet.\n\nThe running shoe and how it has changed\n\n● Daniel and Marcus Rahman experimented with different types of 8………………… used on their shoe uppers.\n\n● Some experimental shoes were banned because of the amount of 9………………… they produced.\n\n● Shoe adjustment is now considered as important as nutrition or 10………………… .\n\n● Early running shoes were usually made from 11………………… .\n\n● Mateo Ruiz had extra steel 12………………… added to the front of his shoes.\n\n● Sofia Almeida changed the 13………………… on her shoes because the original ones were uncomfortable.",
